13. crystallina, vessels of pure white glass. Vitrum here evidently means common glass, more or less coloured as op- posed to the pure crystal white. If crystallina here meant made of the natural crystallum (Pliny, N.H. 37, 28 sqq.) it could not be said to be flawed with glass Becker's Gallus, p. 303. brevi, ‘tiny speck of common glass. '

14. murrina. There have been various opinions about this substance, some maintaining that it was an artificial pro- ductim, a sort of porcelain, others that it was a natural stone. There can be little doubt that the latter is the right view. The confusion has probably arisen from thevfact that the real stone was frequently imitated in glass.
